    "name": "Senescence (Elderly: Age 65+)",
    "biological_shift": "Cellular senescence (zombie cells) accumulation, telomere shortening, and systemic decline in organ function.",
    "metabolic_vulnerabilities": [
      "Anabolic Resistance: Elderly muscles require significantly MORE protein (leucine) to trigger muscle synthesis (mTOR) than young muscles. Failure to meet this causes Sarcopenia (severe muscle wasting), leading to frailty and falls.",
      "Achlorhydria (No Stomach Acid): By age 65, parietal cells in the stomach produce 50% less acid. Without strong acid, the elderly cannot digest protein or ionize Iron/B12. Severe, unexplainable anaemia and neurological decline in the elderly are almost entirely driven by this hidden gut failure, not a poor diet.",
      "Immunosenescence: The thymus gland shrinks to fat (thymic involution), halting production of naive T-cells. The immune system forgets how to fight novel viruses and becomes chronically, uselessly inflamed ('Inflammaging')."
    ],
